<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  proto-mcp hardened-runtime entitlements.

  Phase 7/C. Applied during codesign:
    codesign --options=runtime --entitlements scripts/protonmcp.entitlements ...

  Each entitlement here has a specific justification — keep the list
  minimal. Anything we don't need shouldn't appear.

  Currently enabled:

  * com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory
    Required by the Go runtime — Go binaries map executable memory
    pages at runtime for the goroutine scheduler / cgo stubs and
    macOS's hardened runtime otherwise refuses to load them. This
    is a well-known requirement for ALL Go binaries shipped with
    hardened runtime (Bridge, Docker Desktop, every Go CLI in
    Homebrew uses it).

  Deliberately NOT enabled:

  * com.apple.security.network.client (we open outbound HTTPS to
    Proton — but this entitlement only matters under the App
    Sandbox, which we do NOT enable. Without app-sandbox, network
    is unrestricted by default.)

  * com.apple.security.app-sandbox — would prevent us from opening
    a Unix socket in ~/Library/Application Support, reading the
    Keychain blob via the standard API, and spawning the Touch ID /
    lockwatch helpers. Phase 7 is not a sandboxed app.

  * com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation — we sign all
    our helpers (Touch ID, lockwatch) with the same Team ID, so
    library validation works in our favor. Don't disable it.

  * com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables — DYLD_*
    overrides are a classic exfiltration vector; we never need them.

  Re-check this file every Phase that adds a new helper or runtime
  feature. Adding entitlements is one-way: once shipped, removing
  them silently breaks the user's signed binary on next launch.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
